 {"id":"bd-j3q8m","title":"[HIGH] rch workspace cargo test can lose the built ffs-btrfs test binary before execution","description":"# Review finding

A fresh remote workspace gate failed with infrastructure-style `ENOENT` before running the `ffs-btrfs` unit test binary, even though the build had already progressed through most of the workspace.

## Evidence
- Command: `rch exec -- env CARGO_TARGET_DIR=/tmp/rch_target_frankenfs_cod cargo test --workspace --all-targets`
- Worker/job: `vmi1156319`, job `j-29801994268977526`
- Failure tail:
  - `Running unittests src/lib.rs (/tmp/rch_target_frankenfs_cod/debug/deps/ffs_btrfs-73268ec8690d5672)`
  - `could not execute process ... ffs_btrfs-73268ec8690d5672 (never executed)`
  - `No such file or directory (os error 2)`
- Total runtime before failure: ~468s, after benches and most crates had already run successfully.

## Why this is high severity
This makes the review gate itself nondeterministic. It can mask real product failures behind remote artifact-loss / target-dir-race behavior, which blocks reliable triage and any attempt to prove workspace green.

## Expected fix direction
Investigate remote worker target-dir lifecycle for long `cargo test --workspace --all-targets` runs: artifact eviction, concurrent reuse of `/tmp/rch_target_frankenfs_cod`, or `rch` post-build handling that removes test binaries before execution. Add a deterministic repro or worker-side guard so the built test binary remains executable through the full run.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-22T12:18:09Z","created_by":"cod-fs","updated_at":"2026-04-23T16:46:20.464674786Z","closed_at":"2026-04-23T16:46:20.461887431Z","close_reason":"Out-of-scope for this repo. The failure ('could not execute process .../ffs_btrfs-... No such file or directory (os error 2)' during cargo test --workspace --all-targets) is an rch remote-worker artifact-lifecycle issue — the test binary is built successfully and then disappears before the execution step. Frankenfs's own build/test code is not involved. Fix belongs in the rch repo: worker-side target-dir lifecycle (artifact eviction, concurrent reuse, or post-build cleanup racing execution). No actionable frankenfs change; surfacing per ship-or-surface SLA so triage can move to rch. If the flake reproduces, the rch-side repro is 'rch exec -- env CARGO_TARGET_DIR=/tmp/rch_target_frankenfs_<agent> cargo test --workspace --all-targets' run with other heavy agents concurrently.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["qa","rch","review","workspace-gate"]}
